*Dear Sir, we know that you have always stood up against injustice and that is why we need your help for the very important issue of SSC CGL 2023 examination  (conducted for recruitment of group B central govt officers). The faulty answer key was released in dec 2023 after declaration of the final result. The answer key had more than 5 questions (claimed to be 7 in the court case) for which the answers were wrong. This number is extremely significant considering that the total number of questions in the exam was 130 only. The court case has been ongoing since dec 2023 but the aggrieved students have not got the relaxation they deserve due to legal complexities and lack of attention from national media that NEET exam issue got. We have high hopes from you as the expenses in the legal proceedings have been so much that most petitioners are unable to contribute financially anymore and the time delays have broken them mentally.

The honourable high court (Delhi) had observed in the single bench judgement that one question was wrong so clearly that it did not even need any subject matter expertise, but the court refused to intervene with other questions that were not so straightforward. Although, this proves that other questions are likely to be wrong as well and that is why students have been demanding for an external independent committe since the very beginning, but the court has been reluctant to order for the same. As per the data given by the SSC in the court, nearly 800 candidates out of nearly 8500 total originally selected candidates would be affected only due to change in answer of that one question.The magnitude of this blunder can be understood by considering that even if answers to 4-5 questions (out of total 7 questions challenged) are altered, then the number of candidates affected will be multiple times higher than the current number 800.

In addition, there are a lot of candidates who have been selected in the final result, but their ranks have been affected adversely and as a result either they have not got the post/department or the location which they would have got otherwise. The situation is even worse for some of the petitioners who will be overage for the next exam CGL 2024 and CGL 2023 was their last attempt. Considering all these facts and also that the case is likely to go to supreme court in coming days, we request you to kindly help us as much as possible. We know that you have always stood up against injustice and that is why we believe you will definitely support us.*

A god complex is an unshakable belief characterized by consistently inflated feelings of personal ability, privilege, or infallibility. The person is also highly dogmatic in their views, meaning the person speaks of their personal opinions as though they were unquestionably correct.[1] Someone with a god complex may exhibit no regard for the conventions and demands of society, and may request special consideration or privileges.[1]

God complex is not a clinical term nor diagnosable disorder and does not appear in the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (DSM). The recognized diagnostic name for the behaviors associated with a god complex is narcissistic personality disorder (NPD). A god complex may also be associated with mania or a superiority complex.

The first person to use the term "god complex" was Ernest Jones (1913тАУ51).[2] His description, at least in the contents page of Essays in Applied Psycho-Analysis, describes the god complex as belief that one is a god.[3]

Narendra Modi ji 's tenure as Chief Minister of Gujarat from 2001 to 2014 provides numerous insights into effective governance and development strategies.

*Economic Growth and Industrialization*

- **Investment Promotion**: Modi ji launched the "Vibrant Gujarat" summits to attract global investment, positioning Gujarat as a favorable destination for business. These summits fostered international partnerships and brought significant foreign direct investment (FDI) to the state.
- **Special Economic Zones (SEZs)**: The establishment of SEZs facilitated industrial growth by providing infrastructure and policy incentives, which attracted large corporations and boosted employment.

*Infrastructure Development*

- **Roads and Highways**: Modi ji focused on expanding and improving the state's road network, which facilitated better connectivity and supported economic activities across Gujarat.
- **Ports and Logistics**: Enhancing port infrastructure at locations like Kandla and Mundra turned Gujarat into a major logistics hub, promoting international trade.

*Agricultural and Rural Development*

- **Jyotigram Yojana**: This scheme aimed to provide 24-hour power supply to rural areas, transforming agricultural practices and boosting productivity.
- **Water Management**: Initiatives such as the Sardar Sarovar Project on the Narmada River improved irrigation, addressing water scarcity and supporting agricultural growth.

*Governance Reforms*

- **E-Governance**: Implementation of e-governance initiatives improved transparency, reduced corruption, and made government services more accessible to citizens.
- **SWAGAT Online Program**: This grievance redressal system allowed citizens to directly communicate with the government and seek resolution of their issues, enhancing accountability and responsiveness.

*Education and Health*

- **School Enrollment Programs**: Initiatives like the Kanya Kelavani (Girl Child Education) and Shala Praveshotsav (School Enrollment Drive) increased school enrollment rates, particularly among girls.
- **Healthcare Infrastructure**: Strengthening primary healthcare facilities and launching health insurance schemes improved healthcare access for the rural and urban poor.

*Urban Development*

- **Urban Renewal Projects**: Efforts to modernize cities included improving public transportation, sanitation, and housing, which enhanced the quality of life in urban areas.
- **Cleanliness Drives**: Programs like the "Nirmal Gujarat" campaign focused on cleanliness and hygiene, paving the way for the later national Swachh Bharat Abhiyan.

*Disaster Management*

- **Earthquake Rehabilitation**: Following the 2001 earthquake, Modi ji's government implemented effective rehabilitation and reconstruction programs, setting a benchmark in disaster management and recovery.

*Environmental Initiatives*

- **Green Gujarat**: Afforestation projects and renewable energy initiatives, particularly in solar and wind energy, highlighted a commitment to sustainable development.

*Leadership and Vision*

- **Decisive Leadership**: Modi jiтАЩs ability to make bold decisions and implement them effectively showcased strong leadership qualities.
- **Visionary Planning**: Long-term planning and a clear vision for GujaratтАЩs development helped in setting and achieving ambitious growth targets.

*Lessons for Broader Application*

1. **Proactive Policy Making**: Formulate and implement policies that anticipate future challenges and opportunities.
2. **Public-Private Partnerships**: Leverage collaborations between the government and private sector to drive development.
3. **Citizen-Centric Governance**: Ensure that governance reforms and initiatives are designed to directly benefit the population and address their needs.
4. **Innovation and Technology**: Embrace technological advancements to enhance governance efficiency and service delivery.

In conclusion, Modi ji's tenure as Gujarat CM underscores the importance of dynamic leadership, strategic planning, and inclusive growth in transforming a regionтАЩs socio-economic landscape.

Narendra Modi ji 's tenure as Chief Minister of Gujarat from 2001 to 2014 provides numerous insights into effective governance and development strategies.

*Economic Growth and Industrialization*

- **Investment Promotion**: Modi ji launched the "Vibrant Gujarat" summits to attract global investment, positioning Gujarat as a favorable destination for business. These summits fostered international partnerships and brought significant foreign direct investment (FDI) to the state.
- **Special Economic Zones (SEZs)**: The establishment of SEZs facilitated industrial growth by providing infrastructure and policy incentives, which attracted large corporations and boosted employment.

*Infrastructure Development*

- **Roads and Highways**: Modi ji focused on expanding and improving the state's road network, which facilitated better connectivity and supported economic activities across Gujarat.
- **Ports and Logistics**: Enhancing port infrastructure at locations like Kandla and Mundra turned Gujarat into a major logistics hub, promoting international trade.

*Agricultural and Rural Development*

- **Jyotigram Yojana**: This scheme aimed to provide 24-hour power supply to rural areas, transforming agricultural practices and boosting productivity.
- **Water Management**: Initiatives such as the Sardar Sarovar Project on the Narmada River improved irrigation, addressing water scarcity and supporting agricultural growth.

*Governance Reforms*

- **E-Governance**: Implementation of e-governance initiatives improved transparency, reduced corruption, and made government services more accessible to citizens.
- **SWAGAT Online Program**: This grievance redressal system allowed citizens to directly communicate with the government and seek resolution of their issues, enhancing accountability and responsiveness.

*Education and Health*

- **School Enrollment Programs**: Initiatives like the Kanya Kelavani (Girl Child Education) and Shala Praveshotsav (School Enrollment Drive) increased school enrollment rates, particularly among girls.
- **Healthcare Infrastructure**: Strengthening primary healthcare facilities and launching health insurance schemes improved healthcare access for the rural and urban poor.

*Urban Development*

- **Urban Renewal Projects**: Efforts to modernize cities included improving public transportation, sanitation, and housing, which enhanced the quality of life in urban areas.
- **Cleanliness Drives**: Programs like the "Nirmal Gujarat" campaign focused on cleanliness and hygiene, paving the way for the later national Swachh Bharat Abhiyan.

*Disaster Management*

- **Earthquake Rehabilitation**: Following the 2001 earthquake, Modi ji's government implemented effective rehabilitation and reconstruction programs, setting a benchmark in disaster management and recovery.

*Environmental Initiatives*

- **Green Gujarat**: Afforestation projects and renewable energy initiatives, particularly in solar and wind energy, highlighted a commitment to sustainable development.

*Leadership and Vision*

- **Decisive Leadership**: Modi jiтАЩs ability to make bold decisions and implement them effectively showcased strong leadership qualities.
- **Visionary Planning**: Long-term planning and a clear vision for GujaratтАЩs development helped in setting and achieving ambitious growth targets.

*Lessons for Broader Application*

1. **Proactive Policy Making**: Formulate and implement policies that anticipate future challenges and opportunities.
2. **Public-Private Partnerships**: Leverage collaborations between the government and private sector to drive development.
3. **Citizen-Centric Governance**: Ensure that governance reforms and initiatives are designed to directly benefit the population and address their needs.
4. **Innovation and Technology**: Embrace technological advancements to enhance governance efficiency and service delivery.

In conclusion, Modi ji's tenure as Gujarat CM underscores the importance of dynamic leadership, strategic planning, and inclusive growth in transforming a regionтАЩs socio-economic landscape.

Since Narendra Modi became the Prime Minister of India in 2014, his government has launched numerous initiatives and policies aimed at the development of the country. Here's a detailed explanation of some of the key areas and initiatives:

### 1. **Economic Reforms**

- **Goods and Services Tax (GST):** Implemented in 2017, GST is a unified indirect tax system aimed at simplifying and streamlining the tax structure in India, promoting ease of doing business.
- **Make in India:** Launched in 2014, this initiative encourages companies to manufacture their products in India, boosting industrial growth and employment.
- **Demonetization:** In 2016, high-denomination currency notes (INR 500 and INR 1000) were demonetized to curb black money, counterfeit currency, and promote digital payments.
- **Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code (IBC):** Enacted in 2016, this law aims to consolidate and amend the laws relating to reorganization and insolvency resolution, improving the ease of doing business.

### 2. **Digital India**

- **Digital India Campaign:** Launched in 2015, this initiative focuses on transforming India into a digitally empowered society and knowledge economy, emphasizing digital infrastructure, digital services, and digital literacy.
- **Aadhaar:** Widespread use of the Aadhaar biometric identification system has been promoted for direct benefit transfers, reducing leakages and ensuring efficient delivery of government services.

### 3. **Infrastructure Development**

- **Smart Cities Mission:** Initiated in 2015, this program aims to develop 100 smart cities across India, enhancing the quality of urban living with better infrastructure, technology, and governance.
- **Bharatmala Pariyojana:** Aimed at improving road connectivity, this project focuses on the development of national highways and expressways across the country.
- **Sagarmala Project:** This initiative aims to modernize IndiaтАЩs ports and integrate them with special economic zones (SEZs) to boost coastal and maritime trade.

### 4. **Rural Development**

- **Pradhan Mantri Awas Yojana (PMAY):** Launched in 2015, this scheme aims to provide affordable housing to the urban poor and ensure "Housing for All" by 2022.
- **Swachh Bharat Abhiyan:** Launched in 2014, this nationwide cleanliness campaign aims to eliminate open defecation and improve solid waste management in urban and rural areas.
- **Pradhan Mantri Gram Sadak Yojana (PMGSY):** Aimed at improving rural road connectivity, this initiative focuses on connecting all eligible unconnected habitations with all-weather roads.

### 5. **Social Welfare**

- **Ayushman Bharat:** Launched in 2018, this is the world's largest government-funded healthcare program, providing health insurance coverage to millions of poor and vulnerable families.
- **Ujjwala Yojana:** This scheme, launched in 2016, provides free LPG connections to women from below poverty line (BPL) households, promoting clean cooking fuel.
- **Jan Dhan Yojana:** Launched in 2014, this financial inclusion program aims to ensure access to banking services for all households in the country.

### 6. **Education and Skill Development**

- **Skill India Mission:** Launched in 2015, this initiative aims to train over 400 million people in different skills by 2022, addressing the skill gap and improving employability.
- **New Education Policy 2020:** This policy introduces significant changes in the Indian education system, focusing on holistic, flexible, and multidisciplinary education.

### 7. **Agriculture and Farmers' Welfare**

- **Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi (PM-KISAN):** This income support scheme provides financial assistance to farmers, ensuring minimum income support.
- **E-NAM (National Agriculture Market):** Launched in 2016, this pan-India electronic trading portal aims to create a unified national market for agricultural commodities.

### 8. **Foreign Policy and Diplomacy**

- **Act East Policy:** Aimed at strengthening relations with Southeast Asian countries, enhancing economic and strategic cooperation.
- **Neighborhood First Policy:** Focuses on prioritizing relations with neighboring countries to foster regional stability and cooperation.

These initiatives reflect a broad and ambitious agenda targeting various sectors, aiming for overall development and modernization of the country.

What Are Prophet MuhammadтАЩs Major Miracles?
God performed more than 300 miracles at Prophet MuhammadтАЩs hands which prove his prophethood just as God performed other miracles at the hands of the other prophets and messengers, including Moses and Jesus.

Prophet MuhammadтАЩs major miracles included the split of the moon, Al-IsraтАЩ wa Al-Mi`raj (Night Journey & Ascension to Heaven), the split of his chest, and the fulfillment of all of his prophecies both in his lifetime and after his demise.

However, God favored Prophet Muhammad with an eternal miracle which differs from the rest of his miracles and those of the other prophets and messengers. It is such a miracle which will remain as evidence of his prophethood until the end of the world.

As a matter of fact, Prophet MosesтАЩ miracles included crossing the Red Sea and striking the rock for water to gush out thereof. Prophet JesusтАЩ miracles included making water into wine, causing two thousand pigs to be killed and causing the fig tree to dry up.

Nevertheless, those miracles were limited to the times and places of those two prophets, and they became a history found only in books, for which there is no existing evidence. They may seem as fairy tales for some people.

Still, the QurтАЩan is Prophet MuhammadтАЩs visual, live and eternal miracle. It will remain as reliable evidence of Prophet MuhammadтАЩs prophethood until the Day of Judgment.

Nowadays, in the twenty first century, you can verify the QurтАЩan as a miracle testifying for the prophethood of Prophet Muhammad, whereas we do not find any evidence of the prophethood of Moses or Jesus or the miracles God performed at their hands.
